 for her 18 novels of contemporary British life, including A Village Affair, The Choir and The Rector's Wife, which have often turned on family tensions in agreeable settings.</p><p>She is also the author of 10 historical novels published as Caroline Harvey, scores of short stories, non-fiction and journalism. The archive also includes recordings of interviews and radio and television programmes, as well as speeches and lectures. It covers her work with the Orange Prize, which she has chaired, and  literary bodies including the Society of Authors, the talking books section of the RNIB and the National Literacy Trust.  Trollope was awarded an OBE in  1996 for  services to literature.</p><p>Richard Ovenden, librarian at the Bodleian, said: \"Joanna Trollope's archive gives us an insight into the craft of an immensely popular writer, and a flag-bearer for fiction. Her novels, always handwritten, are meticulously researched and the collection provides an insight into this process.\"</p><p>In the digital age, the Bodleian librarians are particularly pleased to get such a wealth of handwritten material: she says much of her early work was been written on a country kitchen table, though she now writes in <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/jun/03/this-much-know-joanna-trollope\" title=\"\">a handsome study in her  west London home</a>.</p><p>The library will soon start cataloguing the collection to make it available to readers, and will also be exhibiting some of the material.</p><p>Ovenden added: \"Her act of generosity to the Bodleian will be appreciated by literary and cultural historians, and through displays, the public who enjoy her writing so deeply.\"</p><p>Trollope won a scholarship to study English literature  at St Hugh's, Oxford, in the 1960s.  Many authors or their heirs have sold their archives to British or overseas libraries,  and Trollope's would have considerable commercial value.  However, she has chosen to follow the example of another Oxford scholarship author,<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2008/oct/24/alan-bennett-oxford-university\" title=\"\"> Alan Bennett, who also donated his papers to the Bodleian</a> saying the gift was \"in gratitude to the nanny state\".</p>","headline":"Joanna Trollope donates archive to Oxford University's Bodleian Library","trailText":"<p>Best-selling novelist passes on handwritten manuscripts of her novels, as well as letters, journals and research notes</p>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/25/1395763138008/Joanna-Trollope-006.jpg","wordcount":"465","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-03-28T16:01:47Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/mar/25/joanna-trollope-oxford-university-bodleian-library","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/2014/mar/25/joanna-trollope-oxford-university-bodleian-library","tags":[{"id":"books/joanna-trollope","webTitle":"Joanna Trollope","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/joanna-trollope","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/joanna-trollope","references":[]},{"id":"education/oxforduniversity","webTitle":"University of Oxford","type":"keyword","sectionId":"education","sectionName":"Education","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/education/oxforduniversity","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/education/oxforduniversity","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","webTitle":"Books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/books","references":[]},{"id":"culture/culture","webTitle":"Culture","type":"keyword","sectionId":"culture","sectionName":"Culture","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/culture/culture","references":[]},{"id":"uk/uk","webTitle":"UK news","type":"keyword","sectionId":"