etty Images","photographer":"David Levenson","altText":"Joanna Trollope","height":"372","credit":"David Levenson/Getty Images","caption":"Joanna Trollope has been called the inventor of 'the Aga saga' – a term she detests as patronising to her readers. Photograph: David Levenson/Getty Images","width":"620"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/25/1395763147006/Joanna-Trollope-013.jpg","typeData":{"source":"Getty Images","photographer":"David Levenson","altText":"Joanna Trollope","height":"1116","credit":"David Levenson/Getty Images","caption":"Joanna Trollope has been called the inventor of 'the Aga saga' – a term she detests as patronising to her readers. Photograph: David Levenson/Getty Images","width":"1860"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/25/1395763150452/Joanna-Trollope-014.jpg","typeData":{"source":"Getty Images","photographer":"David Levenson","altText":"Joanna Trollope","height":"1536","credit":"David Levenson/Getty Images","caption":"Joanna Trollope has been called the inventor of 'the Aga saga' – a term she detests as patronising to her readers. Photograph: David Levenson/Getty Images","width":"2560"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/25/1395763144140/Joanna-Trollope-011.jpg","typeData":{"source":"Getty Images","photographer":"David Levenson","altText":"Joanna Trollope","height":"276","credit":"David Levenson/Getty Images","caption":"Joanna Trollope has been called the inventor of 'the Aga saga' – a term she detests as patronising to her readers. Photograph: David Levenson/Getty Images","width":"460"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-432992121","relation":"thumbnail","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/25/1395763138008/Joanna-Trollope-006.jpg","typeData":{"source":"Getty Images","photographer":"David Levenson","altText":"Joanna Trollope","height":"84","credit":"David Levenson/Getty Images","caption":"Joanna Trollope has been called the inventor of 'the Aga saga' – a term she detests as patronising to her readers. Photograph: David Levenson/Getty Images","width":"140"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/25/1395763145613/Joanna-Trollope-012.jpg","typeData":{"source":"Getty Images","photographer":"David Levenson","altText":"Joanna Trollope","height":"372","credit":"David Levenson/Getty Images","caption":"Joanna Trollope has been called the inventor of 'the Aga saga' – a term she detests as patronising to her readers. Photograph: David Levenson/Getty Images","width":"620"}}]}]},{"webTitle":"Tips, links and suggestions: What are you reading this week?","webPublicationDate":"2014-03-25T15:56:30Z","sectionName":"Books","sectionId":"books","id":"books/booksblog/2014/mar/25/tips-links-and-suggestions-what-are-you-reading-this-week","fields":{"shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3nzvq","standfirst":"<p>Your space to discuss the books you are reading and what you think of them\n\t\t</p>","hasStoryPackage":"false","body":"<p>Welcome to this week's blog.</p><p>Last week we were bombarded with photos of  readers' towering piles of books, ready for the reading (or re-reading!). This week two of our reviewers have issued a plea in response!</p><p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/discussion/user/id/10247310\">Sara Richards</a></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>It's so nice of all the kind people on here to keep suggesting titles and being so helpful, but can they please desist before I go bankrupt? Or before Book Towers, our beloved home, is left to the mercy of our book collection and we move into a tent on the beach? Will power is useless against the onslaught of such wonderful recommendations.</p></blockquote><p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/discussion/user/id/1263840\">Dylanwolf</a></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>I have the same problem. I'm in a first floor flat and my neighbour in the flat below is complaining about the sagging ceiling directly under the bookshelves... Compulsive behaviour - we're book-buying junkies - what can we do?</p></blockquote><p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/discussion/user/id/10247310\">Sara Richards</a> </p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Books in the attic, books in the shed, books in the bedroom books in the sitting room, books books everywhere. Buying Books Anonymous needs setting up. I will die long before manage to read everything I want to read.</p></blockquote><p><a href=\"http://discussion.theguardian.com/discussion/p/3nh6c?commentpage=1&amp;orderby=oldest&amp;threads=collapsed&amp;tab=all&amp;iframe=true&amp;noposting=true#comment-33388746\"></a><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/discussion/user/id/2174107\"></a><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/discussion/user/id/2174107\">goodyorkshirelass</a> </p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Yep. You think you've got it sorted, and feel pretty smug cos you resisted a couple of tempting titles in the book shop today, and then <a href=\"https://id.theguardian.com/profile/dylanwolf/public\">@Dylanwolf</a> recommends Life: A User's Manual, and all that new found strength crumbles into dust.There's no hope for any of us. Admit defeat.</p></blockquote><p>Do you have any suggestions for these book-recommendation addicts? Should the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog\">Books Blog</a> come with a health warning? Or perhaps the key to managing your towers of books is systematic organisation.</p><p><a href=\"https://witness.theguardian.com/user/Aqilah+Vawda\">Aqilah Vawda</a> has two categories of reading material:</p>  <figure class=\"element element-witness element-witness-image\" itemscope itemtype=\"http://schema.org/ImageObject\" data-media-id=\"https://witness.theguardian.com/assignment/530b584ce4b04f22a42ea34b/876267\"> <div class=\"element-witness--main\">  <a href=\"https://witness.theguardian.com/assignment/530b584ce4b04f22a42ea34b/876267\" itemprop=\"url\"><img src=\"https://n0tice-static.s3.amazonaws.com/image/1394734765806ade4c0f01df8d39d11a3b74a4a6c7dd7-mediumoriginalaspectdouble.jpg\" alt=\"Work v Pleasure\" itemprop=\"contentURL\"/></a>    <figcaption>  <h3 class=\"element-witness--title\" itemprop=\"name\"><a href=\"https://witness.theguardian.com/assignment/530b584ce4b04f22a42ea34b/876267\" itemprop=\"url\">Work v Pleasure</a></h3>   </figcaption>  </div> <footer class=\"element-witness--footer\"> <p class=\"element-witness--source\">Sent via <a href=\"https://witness.theguardian.com/\" class=\"element-witness--brand\" itemprop=\"provider\">GuardianWitness</a></p> <div class=\"element-witness--metadata\"> <p class=\"element-witness--author\" itemprop=\"author\" itemscope itemtype=\"http://schema.org/Person\">  By  <a href=\"https://witness.theguardian.com/user/Aqilah Vawda\" class=\"element-witness--author-name\" itemprop=\"name\">Aqilah Vawda</a> </p> <p class=\"element-witness--date\"> <time itemprop=\"dateCreated\" datetime=\"2014-03-13T18:19:26Z\">13 March 2014, 18:19</time> </p> </div> </footer>  </figure>  <p>Is there a clear divide between 'work' and 'pleasure' reading?</p><p>And how do you sort your books?</p><p>The recent death of Khushwant Singh sparked comment as to why his books remain under-read outside India. Read our obituary of the controversial novelist and short-story writer <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/mar/20/khushwant-singh\">here</a>.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/discussion/user/id/10628952\">TimHannigan</a></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Saddened to note that the mighty Khushwant Singh didn't quite make it to his century.</p><p>Of all the successful Indian writers working in English he must have been by far the most widely read at home, and one of the least read abroad. That might be down to his gloriously irascible character, but it's probably also due to the fact that he never wrote to please and appease a Western audience - so no overwrought family sagas laced with unspoken tragedy; no ornately exotic prose, no gods of big or small things, absolutely no tigers of any colour, and a distinct deficit of mangoes. He was, in short, a thoroughly unsuitable boy, but endlessly entertaining.</p></blockquote><p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/discussion/user/id/11774763\">laidbackviews</a> </p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>It is indeed fascinating; an account of difficult times that we really cannot imagine from the safety of our sofas. The 50th anniversary edition is enhanced by some truly horrifying photos of those dark days.</p><p>Meantime, just finshed Gideon Lewis-Kraus, on pilgrimage to the Camino, to the 88 temples of Shikoku, and finally to Uman, in A Sense of Direction. But his inner journey is immense.</p></blockquote><p>For a contemporary take on rambling and rumination, <a href=\"https://witness.theguardian.com/user/shabbadoo\">shabbadoo</a> recommends Joe Lyman's Don't Let Life Bring You Down.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-witness element-witness-image\" itemscope itemtype=\"http://schema.org/ImageObject\" data-media-id=\"https://witness.theguardian.com/assignment/530b584ce4b04f22a42ea34b/873046\"> <div class=\"element-witness--main\">  <a href=\"https://witness.theguardian.com/assignment/530b584ce4b04f22a42ea34b/873046\" itemprop=\"url\"><img src=\"https://n0tice-static.s3.amazonaws.com/image/13945789546258b5703b27c6e51176e35b1d7aaee916b-mediumoriginalaspectdouble.jpg\" alt=\"Don't Let Life Bring You Down\" itemprop=\"contentURL\"/></a>    <figcaption>  <h3 class=\"element-witness--title\" itemprop=\"name\"><a href=\"https://witness.theguardian.com/assignment/530b584ce4b04f22a42ea34b/873046\" itemprop=\"url\">Don&#39;t Let Life Bring You Down</a></h3>  <div itemprop=\"description\"> <p>Not many novels combine attempts to solve the banking crisis with accidental suicide attempts, passive aggression and soul-searching travel. Most people will relate to this protagonist’s journey through life.</p> </div>   </figcaption>  </div> <footer class=\"element-witness--footer\"> <p class=\"element-witness--source\">Sent via <a href=\"https://witness.theguardian.com/\" class=\"element-witness--brand\" itemprop=\"provider\">GuardianWitness</a></p> <div class=\"element-witness--metadata\"> <p class=\"element-witness--author\" itemprop=\"author\" itemscope itemtype=\"http://schema.org/Person\">  By  <a href=\"https://witness.theguardian.com/user/shabbadoo\" class=\"element-witness--author-name\" itemprop=\"name\">shabbadoo</a> </p> <p class=\"element-witness--date\"> <time itemprop=\"dateCreated\" datetime=\"2014-03-11T23:02:35Z\">11 March 2014, 23:02</time> </p> </div> </footer>  </figure>  <p>Lots of books take us on a journey. But what about books to take on a journey? One site member shared this photo of a beautiful book that enriched a recent trip to Venice.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-witness element-witness-image\" itemscope itemtype=\"http://schema.org/ImageObject\" data-media-id=\"https://witness.theguardian.com/assignment/530b584ce4b04f22a42ea34b/882130\"> <div class=\"element-witness--main\">  <a href=\"https://witness.theguardian.com/assignment/530b584ce4b04f22a42ea34b/882130\" itemprop=\"url\"><img src=\"https://n0tice-static.s3.amazonaws.com/image/13950145572175fec8301b37a7666b31bab7c5b0d85da-mediumoriginalaspectdouble.jpg\" alt=\"The Story of Venice by Thomas Okey 1905\" itemprop=\"contentURL\"/></a>    <figcaption>  <h3 class=\"element-witness--title\" itemprop=\"name\"><a href=\"https://witness.theguardian.com/assignment/530b584ce4b04f22a42ea34b/882130\" itemprop=\"url\">The Story of Venice by Thomas Okey 1905</a></h3>  <div itemprop=\"description\"> <p>A wonderful, part history/part travel guide, book of Venice from 1905. Inscribed inside by the author to his friend George Frampton RA who was the sculptor responsible for the Peter Pan sculpture in Kensington Gardens. George Frampton was also involved in the Venice biennial in 1905.   This was a great book to prepare us for our holiday in Venice last summer.</p> </div>   </figcaption>  </div> <footer class=\"element-witness--footer\"> <p class=\"element-witness--source\">Sent via <a href=\"https://witness.theguardian.com/\" class=\"element-witness--brand\" itemprop=\"provider\">GuardianWitness</a></p> <div class=\"element-witness--metadata\"> <p class=\"element-witness--author\" itemprop=\"author\" itemscope itemtype=\"http://schema.org/Person\">  By  <a href=\"https://witness.theguardian.com/user/guardianUser1811726\" class=\"element-witness--author-name\" itemprop=\"name\">ID6104702</a> </p> <p class=\"element-witness--date\"> <time itemprop=\"dateCreated\" datetime=\"2014-03-17T00:02:37Z\">17 March 2014, 0:02</time> </p> </div> </footer>  </figure>  <p>Which books would you take with with you? <b><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/discussion/user/id/12026842\">fat_hamster</a> </b>asked the giant of all Book Club questions: what is <i>the</i> Desert Island book? Book Club members decided that this did not mean their <i>favourite</i> book.</p><p><b><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/discussion/user/id/10628952\">TimHannigan</a> </b></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>When it comes to a Desert Island book, I've always thought the most important consideration has to be whether you'll be able to read the book over and over. Such a book isn't necessarily \"the best book you've ever read\". But for me there's never been any doubt: my Desert Island book would be Kim by Rudyard Kipling.</p></blockquote><p><b></b></p><p><b><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/discussion/user/id/10395523\">Trevor Edward Walder</a> </b></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Two I would pick. </p><p>The Paladins by John James. The RAF and so much more 1900 - 1940. I'm always getting it down to look something up and re-reading it. </p><p>The Oxford Companion to Ships and the Sea edited by Peter Kemp. A survival manual, an entertainment, a source of myths and links.</p></blockquote><p><b><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/discussion/user/id/10063633\">Mexican2</a></b></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Ulysses. Never lets you down, keeps on giving.</p></blockquote><p>From books you can read again and again to those you only come back to after a long time. <b><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/discussion/user/id/4624105\">Thaizinred</a> </b>wrote about the experience of revisiting Iain Pears's An Instance of the Fingerpost after many years.</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>I started reading it during the summer between high school and college. The terrible grocery store I worked at had a small book section and I would read it when there was no one in the store and I'd already done the inane chores the manager insisted we do (dust the candy, things like that). Sunday morning opening and Saturday night shifts were the best for it. I liked it and made it more than halfway through, but never got around to buying it. Then I went off to school and had plenty of other things to do. I was always a bit curious how it ended, and saw a copy a few months ago in a second hand bookshop.</p><p>Its actually better than I remember, especially now that I know more about the historical figures and time period. At the time I read it initially I had no idea who Boyle or Locke were.</p></blockquote><p>But <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/discussion/user/id/2945051\">kultur</a> had a less satisfying experience when she re-opened The Diving Bell and the Butterfly...</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>which I read well over a decade and found immensely readable, touching in fact, yet somehow looking back it did not seem so believable. This is what books do in the march of time, I suppose.</p></blockquote><p>It isn't just time that can have a diminishing effect – many Book Club readers find that films can spoil enjoyment of the books they are based on. The starting point of discussion was Lionel Shriver's We Need to Talk About Kevin.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/discussion/user/id/12106279\">CapeTownBibliophile</a> </p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>I'm tempted to read it, but I find reading a book after you've seen the film is a recipe for disaster. Case in point: The Prince of Tides. I had seen the film and knew Barbra Streisand played Lowenstein, the psychiatrist character, as well as directing. All throughout the (long) book, the very detailed characterisation of Lowenstein was nothing like Barbra Streisand, and this left me feeling quite exasperated.</p></blockquote><p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/discussion/user/id/12026842\">fat_hamster</a> </p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Please read the book of We Need to talk About Kevin as I think it was brilliantly written. I won't go and see the film in case it ruins the book which I re-read from time to time.</p><p>The book made me wonder if Kevin was \"born evil\" or the result of terrible parenting and whether it is possible to just be an evil person. The suspense she built up was enthralling. I was so tempted to go and see the film but didn't want to have it playing in my head next time I read the book.</p></blockquote><p>But <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/discussion/user/id/1263840\">Dylanwolf</a> disagreed.</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>I'm of the opinion that WHTTAK was an rare example of the film being better than the book.</p><p>Do see the Lynne Ramsay film if you haven't - all three lead actors are superb.</p></blockquote><p>And <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/discussion/user/id/2223929\">aliquidcow</a> recommended sometimes watching the film first, so that abridgements pass unnoticed.</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>I read 12 Years a Slave earlier this year, prior to watching the film. It's a very interesting book, though the style can be a bit distancing at times. I'd perhaps recommend seeing the film first however, since when I got around to seeing it I found myself rather missing a lot of the stuff that had been left out from the book and being a bit disappointed with the shortcuts taken with parts of the story - particularly the denouement.</p></blockquote><ul><br></ul>","headline":"Tips, links and suggestions: What are you reading this week?","trailText":"Your space to discuss the books you are reading and what you think of them\n\t\t","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/24/1395679638989/0367714d-97da-4a22-b128-01a8f41cf8af-140x84.jpeg","wordcount":"1395","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-03-28T15:00:29+00:00"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2014/mar/25/tips-links-and-suggestions-what-are-you-reading-this-week","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/booksblog/2014/mar/25/tips-links-and-suggestions-what-are-you-reading-this-week","tags":[{"id":"books/booksblog","webTitle":"Books blog","type":"blog","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/booksblog","references":[]},{"id":"books/series/tips-links-and-suggestions-books","webTitle":"Tips, links and suggestions","type":"series","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/series/tips-links-and-suggestions-books","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/series/tips-links-and-suggestions-books","references":[]},{"id":"culture/culture","webTitle":"Culture","type":"keyword","sectionId":"culture","sectionName":"Culture","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/culture/culture","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","webTitle":"Books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl"