/Tennessee-Relaxes-008.jpg","typeData":{"source":"Getty Images","photographer":"Express","altText":"Tennessee Relaxes","height":"276","credit":"Express/Getty Images","caption":"'A master of desperation and need'… Tennessee Williams. Photograph: Express/Getty Images","width":"460"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-432992705","relation":"thumbnail","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/25/1395747767421/Tennessee-Relaxes-003.jpg","typeData":{"source":"Getty Images","photographer":"Express","altText":"Tennessee Relaxes","height":"84","credit":"Express/Getty Images","caption":"'A master of showing desperation'… Tennessee Williams. Photograph: Express/Getty Images","width":"140"}}]}]},{"webTitle":"Live webchat with SF writer and Philip K Dick fan Jeff VanderMeer","webPublicationDate":"2014-03-25T11:31:34Z","sectionName":"Books","sectionId":"books","id":"books/2014/mar/25/live-webchat-philip-k-dick-jeff-vandermeer","fields":{"shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3nz32","standfirst":"Is there more to the bewildering Ubik than even Dick himself  would admit? Award-winning writer Jeff VanderMeer will be joining us this Friday to discuss this topic and more","hasStoryPackage":"false","body":"<p>Philip K Dick's Ubik has definitely given us plenty to talk about on this month's reading group. Teasing out this book's many strands, influences and implications has been fascinating – and bewildering. What does it all mean? I'm still not sure. Maybe nothing, if you believe <a href=\"https://archive.org/details/ATalkWithPhilipK.DickOnHour25In1976\" title=\"\">what the author said</a> in 1976:</p><blockquote><p>\"You don't just write whatever comes into your head while you're sitting there in front of the typewriter. When I wrote UBIK, I got about 12 pages done and couldn't think of anything else, so l just wrote whatever came into my mind. I wrote it from my unconscious: I let the right hemisphere of my brain do all the thinking, and I was as surprised as anybody as to what came out. In France, of course, it's considered a great novel because it doesn't make any sense; in France, it's a r<em>oman de pataphysique</em>.\"</p></blockquote><p>Darn it! But the fact that all that complication and drama in Ubik may not add up to anything also enables it to add up to everything. It is a novel of infinite possibility. It's a bravura display of narrative uncertainty. And Dick is a master at holding his readers' attention while everything falls apart.</p><p>All of which makes me very pleased to announce that we're going to be joined by Jeff VanderMeer at 1pm on Friday 28 March for this month's live webchat. Anyone who has read VanderMeer's award-winning fiction – and especially his latest novel <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/mar/05/annihilation-review-jeff-vandermeer-afraid-turn-page\" title=\"\">Annihilation</a> - will be aware that this writer also knows a thing or two about keeping his readers guessing. And since definite answers about Ubik are so hard to come by, it seems a good idea to alter our usual formula slightly and question someone who has an affinity for Dick's kind of writing as well as expertise on the author's life and times.</p><p>Annihilation is full of the unease and mystery that make Dick's books so fascinating – and notably, in fine Philip K Dick style – it was <a href=\"http://www.buzzfeed.com/lincolnmichel/jeff-vandermeer\" title=\"\">inspired by a dream</a>.  Judging by the buzz about the book, and the reviews its been getting, that was an excellent night's work.</p><p>I'm sure it's going to be intriguing to hear about the creation of this work, not to mention VanderMeer's influences, what he thinks of Dick himself and his opinions on the history of this kind of speculative fiction. Although we have invited Jeff primarily as a creative artist, it's also worth noting that he's no slouch on this latter subject, having co-edited a number of highly respected SF anthologies such as <a href=\"http://www.jeffvandermeer.com/2011/08/30/table-of-contents-the-weird-edited-by-ann-and-jeff-vandermeer/\" title=\"\">The Weird</a>. While I'm noting his qualifications, I should also say that he is the winner of two World Fantasy awards as well as a finalist for the Hugo awards and significantly, <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philip_K._Dick_Award\" title=\"\">the Philip K Dick award</a>. (He has also chaired the panel of judges for the latter.)</p><p>But really, I don't need to say much more to introduce Jeff VanderMeer because his words speak for themselves. You can <a href=\"http://io9.com/read-the-mesmerizing-first-chapter-of-jeff-vandermeers-1520682658\" title=\"\">read the first chapter of Annihilation here</a>. Better still, we have copies to give away to the first 10 people to post a relevant question, alongside \"I want a copy please\". And if you're lucky enough to get your request in quickly, don't forget to email <a href=\"mailto:laura.kemp@theguardian.com\" title=\"\">laura.kemp@theguardian.com</a> (Ginny is away for a couple of months) as we can't track you down ourselves – and don't forget to be nice!</p><p>Jeff will be here at 1pm on Friday – but please feel free to get your questions in early, and post now if you don't think you can make the allotted time. Over to you!</p>","headline":"Live webchat with SF writer and Philip K Dick fan Jeff VanderMeer","trailText":"<p><strong>Sam Jordison:</strong> Is there more to the bewildering Ubik than even Dick himself  would admit? Award-winning writer Jeff VanderMeer will be joining us this Friday to discuss this topic and more</p>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/24/1395683351183/Philip-K.-Dick-American-a-003.jpg","wordcount":"594","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-04-30T15:54:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/mar/25/live-webchat-philip-k-dick-jeff-vandermeer","apiUrl":"htt