pact (although, make no mistake, the subject certainly has impact).</p><p>I must admit, though, I struggled with the first few pages. I can't stand&nbsp;the clear-as-a-mountain-creek regular‑guy style so beloved of the faux-masculine tough-but-vulnerable narrative. And for a page or two, <em>Redeployment</em> read to me as if it was&nbsp;written by a rogue Jack Daniels copywriter: \"It was good. We got back on the plane and passed the fuck out. Woke up in America.\" Lots of \"roger\" this and \"roger\" that, and sentences like, \"Sweat a little of the alcohol out,&nbsp;too.\" Here we go, I thought, 300&nbsp;pages&nbsp;from some poor, screwed-up acronym‑spewing marine who finds himself intellectually embarrassed to discover&nbsp;that human beings have rich, deep and dark inner lives. Read <em>War and Peace</em>, soldier.</p><p>I was wrong. This was but a single voice. And, as I read on through the collection, the opening title story revealed itself not to be a sign of&nbsp;limitation but of the book's range. For&nbsp;it is definitely in the combined effect of&nbsp;the&nbsp;stories that <em>Redeployment</em> garners its power and earns the comparisons to <a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/books/98/09/20/specials/obrien-vietnam.html\" title=\"\">Tim O'Brien's writing on Vietnam</a> that it has been getting in America. Indeed, Klay's gifts become more apparent with each new narrator and circumstance: his reach, his tonal&nbsp;control, his observational sophistication, the sheer emotional torque of his narratives. By the end, he&nbsp;had convincingly inhabited more than a dozen different voices and I felt I had learned more about Iraq than in any documentary or factual account.</p><p>In my favourite piece, \"Prayer in the Furnace\", a self-examining chaplain berates himself for daring to suggest that some good would come of suffering. He finds himself \"disgusting\" and \"vile\". He receives a&nbsp;startlingly beautiful letter from his mentor and writes a sermon citing Wilfred Owen. He is compassionate, despairing, desperate, resolved, courageous, cowardly, a foolhardy failure and a dogged success of a man, all at the same time. Not easy to achieve in 38 pages.</p><p>In \"Money as a Weapons System\", which reminded me of Joseph Heller's <em>Catch-22</em>, we witness a brilliantly cast&nbsp;Provincial Reconstruction Team struggle to make sense of the chaos. At&nbsp;great risk to all, the protagonist drives out to a water treatment plant – dark, rusted, locked – trying to locate Kazemi, the chief engineer. Eventually, Kazemi turns up and tells them that the Americans have built the wrong pipes which will deliver water at too&nbsp;great a pressure and blow up thousands of Sunni bathrooms; but as a Shi'a, he's loath to turn on the water for Sunnis because he'll be murdered. Nothing happens. Kazemi is killed anyway. Meanwhile, the team are delivered a consignment of baseball uniforms by a millionaire philanthropist, \"the mattress king of northern Kansas\", before they move on to a bee-keeping project with a handful of Iraqi widows.</p><p>Here we have a series of increasingly sophisticated portraits of&nbsp;men pulled apart by competing and&nbsp;contradictory feelings. It's no coincidence that Klay's secondary subject is male sexuality – its isolation, its neediness, its lust, pride, sometime sensitivity, sometime cauterisation. He&nbsp;writes with striking perception and&nbsp;unusual honesty about his soldiers' relationships with wives, girlfriends and lap dancers, as&nbsp;well as the Iraqi girls they see (often&nbsp;through cross hairs). There's some funny stuff – a platoon all get herpes because they're using the same \"pocket pussy\". There's some brutal stuff – an anecdote in the story \"In Vietnam They Had Whores\" that I'll leave you to read. But it is interesting that the horror of war allows Klay to smuggle in an uncustomary male frankness that makes Roth, Amis and&nbsp;the gang look elliptical and effete.</p><p>The thing that impressed me most, though, was Klay's behind-the-scenes skill with language. For the most part, the stories are planed and worked in that meticulous American manner. The&nbsp;dialogue is a lesson in how to render the rhythms of natural speech. And the poetical moments arise organically – as&nbsp;when in <a href=\"http://www.guernicamag.com/daily/phil-klay-ten-kliks-south/\" title=\"\">\"Ten Kliks South\"</a> an artilleryman tells us, \"I saw&nbsp;fires through the haze, or not even&nbsp;fires, just flashes of red in the dust and&nbsp;cordite.\"</p><p>To my mind, there are three stories that are not of the highest standard – the least convincing being \"Psychological Operations\", in which the conversation long outlasts its dramatic plausibility. But <em>Redeployment</em> is a must-read for anyone with the slightest interest in the actuality of the wars that have been&nbsp;fought in our names.</p><p>• Edward Docx's <em>The Devil's Garden</em> is published by Picador.</p>","headline":"Redeployment by Phil Klay review –  'Incendiary stories of war'","trailText":"Ex-marine Phil Klay inhabits more than a dozen different voices in these compelling short stories of conflict in Iraq and Afghanistan, writes <strong>Edward Docx</strong>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Books/Pix/pictures/2014/3/20/1395337023751/The-shadow-of-an-Iraqi-so-004.jpg","wordcount":"892","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-05-09T16:30:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/mar/26/redeployment-phil-klay-review-incendiary-stories-of-war","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/2014/mar/26/redeployment-phil-klay-review-incendiary-stories-of-war","tags":[{"id":"books/fiction","webTitle":"Fiction","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/fiction","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/fiction","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","webTitle":"Books","type":"keyword","sectionI