ing bedtime reading at the end of a chapter, knowing the book will wait patiently, bookmark in place, for the following night. To me, the best ones offer the same intoxicating, seamless interaction between text and image that a good picture book does, with an additional sense of challenge and excitement imparted by a more sustained, developed narrative.</p><p>Clear leader of the pack is <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2013/sep/18/review-dixie-o-day-fast-lane-shirley-hughes-clara-vulliamy\" title=\"\">Dixie O'Day: In the Fast Lane</a>, a charming collaboration between the brilliant mother-and-daughter team <a href=\"http://www.dixieoday.com/meet-shirley-and-clara/\" title=\"\">Shirley Hughes and Clara Vulliamy</a>.  In a gentle, welcoming, red-and-pink world, a Snoopy/Wacky Racers mashup seen through rose-tinted glasses, live Dixie O'Day and his diminutive pal Percy, who take great care of Dixie's beloved old car. One day, they set out to race a motley assortment of vehicles – including the shiny new convertible driven by their neighbour and nemesis, Louella, in her \"special motoring hat\" – from Didsworth to Dodsworth, having several small, self-contained adventures en route. Dixie's illustrations and words feel instantly timeless and classic – and I give in to pleas for \"just one chapter\" with the minimum of arm-twisting.</p><p>A similarly jaunty and insouciant note is struck by <a href=\"http://claudebooks.blogspot.co.uk/\" title=\"\">Claude, Alex T Smith's cheerfully adventurous beret-wearing dog</a>, and his best friend Sir Bobblysock. Claude's slightly manic, wide-eyed grin as he bimbles about town unbeknown to his owners, Mr and Mrs Shinyshoes, is sure to be mirrored on the face of the reader soaking up his surreal antics.</p><p>Pip Jones's big-eyed adventures of Ava and her naughty invisible cat, <a href=\"http://www.faber.co.uk/catalog/squishy-mcfluff-the-invisible-cat/9780571302505\" title=\"\">Squishy McFluff</a>, will also be a surefire hit with any kid who's ever devolved responsibility for wickedness or mishap to a sibling or imaginary friend. Chapter by chapter, we saunter through an elegantly depicted landscape, lulled by smooth-flowing rhyme, but gradually realising who may really be behind the book's series of dreadful deeds …</p><p>And for those who enjoy gleeful gross-outs, Tim Healey and Chris Mould provide rhyming adventures of a very different kind – the \"madcap plans and crazy ideas\" of <a href=\"https://www.hachettechildrens.co.uk/books/detail.page?isbn=9780340997734\" title=\"\">Mortimer Keene</a>, a juvenile inventor and slime-flooder of schools whose brain has been overheated by an excess of homework. These books sneakily teach words such as \"viscous\" and \"bitumen\", while delighting wobbly-legged early readers with their rousing bounce and swing.</p><p>What other books do you think best bridge the gap between the beloved titles of toddlerhood and the giddy heights of <a href=\"http://www.seaquestbooks.co.uk/\" title=\"\">BeastQuest</a> and <a href=\"http://www.rainbowmagiconline.com/uk/books/books_rainbow.html\" title=\"\">Rainbow Magic</a>?</p>","headline":"Children's picture and chapter books: titles that bridge the gap","trailText":"<strong>Imogen Russell Williams:</strong> When picture books seem 'too babyish' these longer illustrated books can help children move up to the next level","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2014/3/24/1395684262168/Shirley-Hughes-and-her-da-006.jpg","wordcount":"526","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-04-01T17:08:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/mar/25/childrens-picture-chapter-books-titles-illustrated","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/2014/mar/25/childrens-picture-chapter-books-titles-illustrated","tags":[{"id":"books/series/imogen-russell-williams-children-s-library","webTitle":"Imogen Russell Williams' children's library","type":"series","