e said that, it was one of his great gags with a solid vein of truth in it; now, the&nbsp;truth is even more obvious. Only Dickens can compete on such terms; and if you go by output alone, Balzac blows him away. I would also say that delightful and brilliant though Dickens is, Balzac is quite simply the superior novelist, more on the alert against mawkishness. You can't imagine a&nbsp;Wildeism about Balzac along the lines&nbsp;of only a heart of stone not being moved to laughter by the death of Little Nell. Balzac is, basically, more grown up. You get the sense that you&nbsp;are reading an undeceived, undeceivable adult – albeit one with a&nbsp;highly developed sense of the melodramatic, and the potency of story itself. Many of his stories are enfolded within themselves – narrator passing on the story told by a character he meets, etc – and sometimes I found myself thinking of a large-scale version of the miniaturist Stefan Zweig.</p><p>Again and again, though, Balzac returns, obliquely but obsessively, to&nbsp;the fact of his extraordinary facility for creation; his characters lose themselves in thoughts and imaginings about the lives of people they see in the street. One of his most intriguing and compelling characters, the money-lender Gobseck in the eponymous story, describes himself as you imagine Balzac might: \"Do you think it's nothing, this power to see into the most secret recesses of the human heart, to engage another person's heart, to see it all stripped naked? It&nbsp;is&nbsp;always drama, always different: hideous wounds, deathly sorrows, love scenes, griefs likely to end beneath the waters of the Seine, a young man's pleasures that lead to the scaffold, despairing laughter, and sumptuous celebrations.\" That, essentially, is Balzac's work: never a dull moment, with ruin or scandal always but a step&nbsp;away, lovers declaring that they must love so-and-so or die – and then delivering on that oath. (This occurs in&nbsp;\"Sarrasine\".)</p><p>Balzac was also incredibly influential. Without him, no Proust, no&nbsp;Flaubert, and – who knows? – no&nbsp;realism. He was also one of the novelists who appreciated that, above all, a novel is a means of transport between very different modes of experience. He wanted, in real life, to&nbsp;build a spiral staircase between the&nbsp;Jardin de Luxembourg and the catacombs beneath; and that's a fairly obvious metaphor for how he saw his grand work, as a bridge between the highest and lowest of society. And the&nbsp;great thing about work this entertaining is that it's still exciting nearly 200 years on; so it isn't just a bridge, it's a fully functioning time machine. I strongly recommend you&nbsp;hop in.</p>","headline":"The Human Comedy: Selected Stories by Honoré de Balzac – review","trailText":"<strong>Nicholas Lezard's paperback of the week: </strong>Here is an extremely elegant way to experience the joys of Balzac without learning French","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/24/1395680214565/Honore-de-Balzac-006.jpg","wordcount":"646","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-05-09T17:00:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/mar/25/human-comedy-balzac-review-nicholas-lezard","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/2014/mar/25/human-comedy-balzac-review-nicholas-lezard","tags":[{"id":"books/fiction-in-translation","webTitle":"Fiction in translation","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/fiction-in-translation","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/fiction-in-translation","references":[]},{"id":"books/fiction","webTitle":"Fiction","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/fiction","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/books/fiction","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","webTitle":"Books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webU